04796nam a22005295i 9780226496047DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018014122  a9780226496047  a(DE-B1597)550062  a(OCoLC)1055049812  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQ172.5.P77bP54 2018 4aQ172.5.P77bP54 2018 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a001.9223  aTB 62002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/143786:1 aPigliucci, Massimo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNonsense on Stilts /cMassimo Pigliucci. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Science versus Pseudoscience and the “Demarcation Problem” -- tChapter One. Frustrating Conversations -- tChapter Two. Hard Science, Soft Science -- tChapter Three. Almost Science -- tChapter Four. Pseudoscience -- tChapter Five. Blame the Media? -- tChapter Six. Debates on Science -- tChapter Seven. From Superstition to Natural Philosophy -- tChapter Eight. From Natural Philosophy to Modern Science -- tChapter Nine. The Science Wars I -- tChapter Ten. The Science Wars II -- tChapter Eleven. The Problem and the (Possible) Cure -- tChapter Twelve. Who’s Your Expert? -- tConclusion. So, What Is Science after All? -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecent polls suggest that fewer than 40 percent of Americans believe in Darwin’s theory of evolution, despite it being one of science’s best-established findings. Parents still refuse to vaccinate their children for fear it causes autism, though this link has been consistently disproved. And about 40 percent of Americans believe that the threat of global warming is exaggerated, including many political leaders. In this era of fake news and alternative facts, there is more bunk than ever. But why do people believe in it? And what causes them to embrace such pseudoscientific beliefs and practices? In this fully revised second edition, noted skeptic Massimo Pigliucci sets out to separate the fact from the fantasy in an entertaining exploration of the nature of science, the borderlands of fringe science, and—borrowing a famous phrase from philosopher Jeremy Bentham—the nonsense on stilts. Presenting case studies on a number of controversial topics, Pigliucci cuts through the ambiguity surrounding science to look more closely at how science is conducted, how it is disseminated, how it is interpreted, and what it means to our society. The result is in many ways a “taxonomy of bunk” that explores the intersection of science and culture at large. No one—neither the public intellectuals in the culture wars between defenders and detractors of science nor the believers of pseudoscience themselves—is spared Pigliucci’s incisive analysis in this timely reminder of the need to maintain a line between expertise and assumption. Broad in scope and implication, Nonsense on Stilts is a captivating guide for the intelligent citizen who wishes to make up her own mind while navigating the perilous debates that will shape the future of our planet.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPseudosciencexHistory. 0aSciencexHistory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aamerica, american, academic, scholarly, research, darwin, darwinian, theory of evolution, theoretical, science, scientific, vaccines, vaccination, autism, global warming, conspiracy theories, politics, political, government, alternative facts, fake news, viral, pseudoscientist, belief, skeptics, intellectual, culture war, cultural, epistemology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Pack